%S A397501 1,2,3,3,3,5,4,9,10,17,6,33,6,73,32,129,10,257,18,513,52,1025,34,2049,
%T A397501 122,4097,68,8193,66,17409,130,33089,388,65537,322,131085,258,262145,
%U A397501 532,524289,514,1063937,1026,2097153,3140,4194305,2050,8912897,4098
%N A397501 a(n) is the number of set partitions of {0, ..., n} in which, for every part P, the sum of binomial(n, k) over k in P is a power of 2.
%C A397501 Every valid partition corresponds to a partition of the total weight 2^n into powers of 2, with multiplicities equal to the numbers of parts having a given part sum.
%C A397501 The weights are the entries binomial(n, k) of row n of Pascal's triangle. Powers of 2 arise naturally from the identity Sum_{k = 0 .. n} binomial(n, k) = 2^n.
%C A397501 Odd n: pairing k with n - k shows a(n) >= 2^((n - 1)/2) + 1; choose exactly one index from each pair {k, n - k} to form a 2-part partition whose two part sums are both 2^(n - 1), plus the 1-part partition with sum 2^n.
%C A397501 For odd n, balanced 2-block partitions with block sums 2^(n - 1) correspond to nontrivial {-1, 0, 1}-relations among binomial(n, 0), ..., binomial(n, (n - 1)/2); see A397551.
%C A397501 Conjecture (odd n): a(n) = 2^((n - 1)/2) + 1 + A397551(n).
%C A397501 Even n: structure is subtler due to the central term binomial(n, n/2) and its 2-adic valuation; closed forms are unknown.
%H A397501 Felix Huber, <a href="/A397501/a397501.txt">Maple program</a>
%F A397501 a(n) >= 2^((n - 1)/2) + 1 for odd n.
%F A397501 Conjecture (odd n): a(n) = 2^((n - 1)/2) + 1 + A397551(n).
%e A397501 n = 3: row [1, 3, 3, 1]; valid: {0, 1} | {2, 3} -> 4 | 4, {0, 2} | {1, 3} -> 4 | 4, {0, 1, 2, 3} -> 8; hence a(3) = 3.
%e A397501 n = 4: row [1, 4, 6, 4, 1]; valid partitions: {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} -> 16, {0, 2, 4} | {1, 3} -> 8 | 8, {0, 2, 4} | {1} | {3} -> 8 | 4 | 4; hence a(4) = 3.
%e A397501 n = 5: row [1, 5, 10, 10, 5, 1]; choosing one element from each pair {0, 5}, {1, 4}, {2, 3} gives 2^3 = 8 choices, but complementary choices yield the same unordered 2-part partition, hence 4 distinct unordered 2-part partitions, each with part sums 16 and 16, plus {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} -> 32; hence a(5) = 5.
%p A397501 # See Huber link.
